Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made for February, 2019 in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area and New York city.These bike share systems, with hundreds of stations and thousands of bikes across both cities. Its a fun, affordable and convenient way to get around.

The New York city datasets appear to have more records than the San Francisco area, with total records of 943,744, and 15 features. It can also be noticed, the two datasets share different column names even though they have the same feature. For the purpose of merging the both dataset, we would rename columns of NYC to the same as CA dataset columns in the cleaning phase.

DATA CLEANING¶

At this phase of our analysis, we would be concentrating on cleaning some features in order to get our datasets ready for analysis. Some of which are:

  • Dropping records with missing entries in the San Francisco bay area.
  • Editing column names in New York city to be the same as the San Francisco bay area.
  • Extracting samples without replacement from New York city to be the same as the San Francisco area.
  • Replace the numeric values in NYC member gender from 0, 1 and 2, to Other, Male and Female respectively.
  • Add city code to New York City (NYC), and San Francisco CA for easy record referencing after merging.
  • Merging all the datasets to form a master copy.
  • Change start and end time to datetime type and so on.

Let's now proceed to the clean up operation.

Next, We would be making user_type, member_gender, state_code, and age_category into ordered categorical types.

DEFINE

  • Making user_type,member_gender, state code, and age_category a categorical type

CODE

In [31]:
# making user_type, member_gender, state code, and age category into ordered categorical type.
ordinal_var_dict = {'member_gender':['Male','Other', 'Female'],'user_type':['Customer', 'Subscriber'],
                    'state_code':['NYC','CA'], 'age_category':["Teens","Young_Adults","Middle-aged_Adults","old_Adults"]}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    master_bike_df[var] = master_bike_df[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The above data sets contains 349,904 records and 18 features (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, member_age, state_code, and bike_share_for_all_trip). Most of the features are strings, and float in nature, but user_type, member_gender, state_code, and age_category are ordered levels with the following levels.

  • User type: Customer, Subscriber
  • member_gender: Male, Other, Female
  • state_code: NYC, CA
  • age_category : Teens, Young_Adults, Middle_aged_adults, Old_Adults

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in comparing the two states, NYC and CA. Afterwhich, I plan in figuring out what factors are best for predicting the duration of Individual bike ride in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect the user_type and member_age will have the strongest effect on the duration of an individual bike ride.

def dist_plot(arg,size,xliml,xlimu):
    '''Plotting on a standard scaled plot'''   
    bins = np.arange(0, master_bike_df[arg].max()+size, size)
    plt.figure(figsize=[10, 8])
    plt.hist(data = master_bike_df, x = arg, bins = bins)
    plt.xlabel(arg)
    plt.xlim(xliml,xlimu)
    plt.show()
    
dist_plot('duration_sec',200,0,5500)

The distribution appears to be skewed to the right, with a lot of bike rides at the lower duration, lying less than 5000, with its peak between 0 and 1000. Let's consider a transformation to obtain better insights.

In [37]:
# Plotting using log transformation
def dist_trans(arg,size):
    ''' Plotting on a log transformation'''
    maximum = np.log10(master_bike_df[arg].max())
    minimum = np.log10(master_bike_df[arg].min())
    bins = 10 ** np.arange(minimum,maximum + size, size)
    plt.figure(figsize=[10,8])
    plt.hist(data=master_bike_df, x=arg, bins=bins)
    plt.xscale('log')
    #plt.xticks([100,1e3,1e4,1e5,1e6],[100,'1k','10k','100k','1M'])
    plt.xlabel(arg)
    plt.show()


dist_trans('duration_sec',0.105)

Plotting on a log scale, the duration is highly concentrated at the centre, with a unimodal shape. Its peak is between 500 and 1000. Next up, is the age distribution.

# compute the logarithm transformation of age and duration make plotting easier
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """ quick function for computing log and power operations """
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)

master_bike_df['log_duration'] = master_bike_df['duration_sec'].apply(log_trans)
master_bike_df['log_age'] = master_bike_df['member_age'].apply(log_trans)

Conclusions¶

The analysis of February bike rides from the San Francisco bay area and New York city was obtained for analysis. cleanup operations were required to get the dataset ready for analysis. No tidiness issues were addressed during the course of analysis, and overall insight shows no significant relationship between age and duration. All categorical variables shows no relationships rather than more participation of male subscribers on Thursdays. It was also observed there are more subscriber to customers, of which are more males than females, with teens and young adults, of age 18 - 34 taking majority of the members in both city datasets. The duration and age variable took on a large range of values, highly skewed to the right with a long tail. As result, I looked at the data using a log transform. Under the transformation, the data looked unimodal, with duration peak between 500 and 1000, and age distribution between 25 to 50 for the overall datasets.

Limitations¶

Inability to download data from given sites, to include more cities and yearly analysis.
